const faqs = [
 { q: 'What is embroidery?', a: 'Embroidery is a decoration method that stitches a design directly into fabric using thread. A digital file (the "stitch file") tells a multi-needle embroidery machine where to place each stitch — building up a design out of thousands of individual stitches in different colors. The result is a textured, durable design that\'s woven into the fabric rather than printed on top.' },
 { q: 'How does an embroidery machine work?', a: 'A commercial multi-needle machine clamps the garment into a hoop, then moves the hoop in X/Y axes under a stationary needle that\'s threaded with one of multiple color spools. The machine reads a stitch file and places each stitch in sequence, switching needles automatically when a color change is needed. A 6-head machine does this on six garments simultaneously.' },
 { q: 'What\'s the embroidery process from logo to finished shirt?', a: 'Six steps: (1) digitize the logo into a stitch file, (2) hoop the garment to hold it taut, (3) load the stitch file into the machine, (4) thread the machine with the colors needed, (5) run the machine — typically 5-15 minutes per garment depending on stitch count, (6) trim loose threads and inspect. Repeat across the order quantity.' },
 { q: 'How is embroidery different from screen printing?', a: 'Embroidery stitches thread into the fabric; screen printing pushes ink through a mesh stencil onto the surface. Embroidery has texture and dimension; screen printing is flat. Embroidery handles small detailed logos on knits and wovens; screen printing handles large bold designs at volume. Most companies use both — embroidery on polos and hats, screen printing on tees and hoodies.' },
 { q: 'What makes a logo embroider well?', a: 'Bold, simple designs with distinct elements work best. Fine lines under 1mm wide can drop out; very small text becomes illegible; gradients don\'t translate to thread. The cleanest embroidery comes from logos that were designed for embroidery or simplified for stitch — a "stitch-optimized" version of a complex logo often looks better than the original.' },
 { q: 'Can you embroider on any fabric?', a: 'Most fabrics yes — cotton, polyester blends, performance fabrics, denim, canvas, and leather (with sewn-on patches) all embroider. Knit fabrics (polos, t-shirts) need backing material to keep the stitches stable; very stretchy fabrics (some performance polos) require special hooping. Solo polyester (polos, athletic wear) embroiders cleanly without dye-migration concerns.' },
 { q: 'How long has embroidery been around?', a: 'Hand embroidery dates back thousands of years across many cultures. Industrial embroidery machines have been around since the late 1800s; modern computer-controlled multi-needle embroidery machines (the kind used in commercial shops today) became standard in the 1980s. The fundamental process — building a design out of stitches — is unchanged.' },
]

